141 tb->item[i].nbits = tb->item[i].nbits_ori;

144 }
145 tb->x_start[0] = 0; // fix the start for x = 0
146 fclose ( t );
147 tb->nlines = i;
148 tb->wmo_table = 1;
149 strcpy ( tb->old_path, tb->path ); // store latest path

678 if ( b->state.stat1_active && l->lseq[i].x == 24 && l->lseq[i].y == 255 )
679 {
680 k = b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->bitmap_to[ixloop];
681
682 // Get the bitmaped descriptor k
683 if ( ixloop == 0 )
684 {
685 b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->stat1[b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->ns1 -1] = s->nd;
686 }
687
688 if ( bufrdeco_tableB_val ( & ( s->sequence[s->nd] ), b, & ( l->lseq[k] ) ) )
689 {
690 return 1;
691 }
692
693 s->sequence[s->nd].related_to = b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->bitmap_to[ixloop];
694 if ( s->nd < ( s->dim - 1 ) )
695 {
696 s->nd += 1;
697 }
698 else
699 {
700 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): Reached limit. Consider increas BUFR_NMAXSEQ\n", __func__ );
701 return 1;
702 }
703 }
704
705 // Case of difference statistics
706 //
707 // This operator shall signify a data item containing a
708 // difference statistical value of the type indicated by
709 // the preceding 0 08 024 element descriptor; the
710 // element descriptor to which the difference statistical
711 // value relates is obtained by the application of the
712 // data present bit-map associated with the difference
713 // statistical values follow operator; difference statistical
714 // values shall be represented as defined by this
715 // element descriptor, but with a reference value of 2**n
716 // and a data width of (n+1), where n is the data width
717 // given by the original descriptor. This special reference
718 // value allows the statistical difference values to
719 // be centred around zero.
720 if ( b->state.dstat_active && l->lseq[i].x == 25 && l->lseq[i].y == 255 )
721 {
722 k = b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->bitmap_to[ixloop];
723
724 // Get the bitmaped descriptor k
725 if ( ixloop == 0 )
726 {
727 b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->stat1[b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->nds -1] = s->nd;
728 }
729
730 // in bufrdeco_tableB_val() is taken into acount when is difference statistics active
731 if ( bufrdeco_tableB_val ( & ( s->sequence[s->nd] ), b, & ( l->lseq[k] ) ) )
732 {
733 return 1;
734 }
735
736 /*s->sequence[s->nd].ref = - ( ( int32_t ) 1 << s->sequence[s->nd].bits );
737 s->sequence[s->nd].bits++;*/
738 s->sequence[s->nd].related_to = b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->bitmap_to[ixloop];
739 if ( s->nd < ( s->dim - 1 ) )
740 {
741 s->nd += 1;
742 }
743 else
744 {
745 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): Reached limit. Consider increas BUFR_NMAXSEQ\n", __func__ );
746 return 1;
747 }
748 }
749
750 break;
751
752 case 3:
753 // Case of sequence descriptor
754 if ( bufrdeco_decode_subset_data_recursive ( s, l->sons[i], b ) )
755 {
756 return 1;
757 }
758 break;
759
760 default:
761 // this case is not possible
762 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): Found bad 'f' in descriptor\n", __func__ );
763 return 1;
764 break;
765 }
766 }
767 }
768 return 0;
769}

◆ bufrdeco_extract_bufr()

int bufrdeco_extract_bufr ( struct bufrdeco *  b,
char *  filename 
)

Read file and try to find a bufr report inserted in. Once found do the same that bufrdeco_read_file()

Parameters
bpointer to struct bufrdeco
filenamecomplete path of BUFR file

This function does the folowing tasks:

  • Try to find first buffer of bytes begining with 'BUFR' chars and ending with '7777'. This will be considered as a bufr file.
  • Read the file and checks the marks at the begining and end to see wheter is a BUFR file
  • Init the structs and allocate the needed memory if not done previously
  • Splits and parse the BUFR sections (without expanding descriptors nor parsing data)
  • Reads the needed Table files and store them in memory.

Returns 0 if all is OK, 1 otherwise

< pointer to a memory buffer where we write raw bufr file

195 size = end - beg + 1;
196 }
197 }
198
199
200 // close the file
201 fclose ( fp );
202
203 if ( size < 8 )
204 {
205 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): not found a '7777' item after 'BUFR'\n", __func__ );
206 return 1;
207 }
208 res = bufrdeco_read_buffer ( b, pbeg, size );
209 free ( bufrx );
210 return res;
211}

◆ bufrdeco_get_bufr()

int bufrdeco_get_bufr ( struct bufrdeco *  b,
char *  filename 
)

Read file and try to find a bufr report inserted in. Once found do the same that bufrdeco_read_bufr()

Parameters
bpointer to struct bufrdeco
filenamecomplete path of BUFR file

This function does the folowing tasks:

  • Try to find first buffer of bytes begining with 'BUFR' chars and ending with '7777'. This will be considered as a bufr file.
  • Read the file and checks the marks at the begining and end to see wheter is a BUFR file
  • Init the structs and allocate the needed memory for raw data if not done previously
  • Splits and parse the BUFR sections (without expanding descriptors nor parsing data)
  • Reads the needed Table files and store them in memory.

Returns 0 if all is OK, 1 otherwise

int bufrdeco_increase_data_array ( struct bufrdeco_subset_sequence_data *  s)

doubles the allocated space for a struct bufrdeco_subset_sequence_data whenever is posible

Parameters
spointer to source struct bufrdeco_subset_sequence_data

The amount of data in a bufr must be huge. In a first moment, the dimension of a sequence of structs bufr_atom_data is BUFR_NMAXSEQ but may be increased. This function task is try to double the allocated dimension and reallocate it.

Return 0 when success, otherwise return 1 and the struct is unmodified

◆ bufrdeco_parse_compressed()

int bufrdeco_parse_compressed ( struct bufrdeco_compressed_data_references *  r,
struct bufrdeco *  b 
)

Preliminary parse of a compressed data bufr.

Parameters
rpointer to a struct bufrdeco_compressed_data_references where to set the results
bbasic container struct bufrdeco

When a bufr report has compressed data, it is needed to do a first parse step to get references about where to find the data for every descriptor in subsets. This is what this function does. If succeeded the struct r will have all needed data to decode individual subsets.

Also be mind that the descriptors tree have to be already parsed when calling this function

Returns 0 if succeeded, 1 otherwise

82 struct bufrdeco_compressed_ref *rf;
83 struct bufr_replicator replicator;
84

87 return 1;

91 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): Unspected NULL argument\n", __func__ );
92 return 1;
93 }

95 if ( l == NULL )

98 // At the moment there are no structs bufrdeco_compressed_ref used
99 r->nd = 0;
100 // set the auxiliar pointer at the begining of array of sequences of bufrdeco_expanded_tree
101 seq = & ( b->tree->seq[0] );
102 // Cleans the state of parsing
103 memset ( & ( b->state ), 0, sizeof ( struct bufrdeco_decoding_data_state ) );
104 // and set some other initial values
105 b->state.bit_offset = 0;
106 b->state.added_bit_length = 0;
107 b->state.added_scale = 0;
108 b->state.added_reference = 0;

114 b->state.quality_active = 0;

121 // We just set the auxiliar index
122 seq = l;
123 }

125 // loop for a sequence
126 for ( i = 0; i < seq->ndesc ; i++ )
127 {
128 // switch according to 'f' of the descriptor of sequence
129 switch ( seq->lseq[i].f )
130 {
131 case 0:
132 // Checks if no_data_present is active for this descriptor in this sequence
133 if ( seq->no_data_present.active &&
134 i >= seq->no_data_present.first &&
135 i <= seq->no_data_present.last )
136 {
137 // If here then no_data_present has been active in this sequence
138 if ( seq->lseq[i].x > 9 &&
139 seq->lseq[i].x != 31 )
140 {
141 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): Getting data from table b with class other than 1-9,31 and no data present activated\n", __func__ );
142 return 1;
143 }
144
145 }
146
147 // Get data from table B

149
150 // First the the data itself
151 if ( bufrdeco_tableB_compressed ( rf, b, & ( seq->lseq[i] ), 0 ) )
152 {
153 return 1;
154 }
155
156 //case of first order statistics
157 if ( b->state.stat1_active &&
158 seq->lseq[i].x == 8 && seq->lseq[i].y == 23 )
159 {
160 k = b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->ns1; // index un stqts
161 b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->stat1_desc[k] = r->nd; // Set the value of statistical parameter
162 // update the number of quality variables for the bitmap
163 if ( k < BUFR_MAX_QUALITY_DATA )
164 ( b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->ns1 )++;
165 else
166 {
167 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): No more space for first order statistic vars in bitmap. Check BUFR_MAX_QUALITY_DATA\n", __func__ );
168 return 1;
169 }
170 }
171
172 //case of difference statistics
173 if ( b->state.dstat_active &&
174 seq->lseq[i].x == 8 && seq->lseq[i].y == 24 )
175 {
176 k = b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->nds; // index un stqts
177 b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->dstat_desc[k] = r->nd; // Set the value of statistical parameter
178 // update the number of quality variables for the bitmap
179 if ( k < BUFR_MAX_QUALITY_DATA )
180 ( b->bitmap.bmap[b->bitmap.nba - 1]->nds )++;
181 else
182 {
183 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): No more space for difference statistic vars in bitmap. Check BUFR_MAX_QUALITY_DATA\n", __func__ );
184 return 1;
185 }
186 }
187
188 // Set the used elements of array in r
189 if ( r->nd < ( BUFR_NMAXSEQ - 1 ) )
190 {
191 r->nd += 1;
192 }
193 else
194 {
195 // no more space
196 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): Reached limit. Consider increas BUFR_NMAXSEQ\n", __func__ );
197 return 1;
198 }
199
200 // Then we check for an associated field
201 rf = & ( r->refs[r->nd] );
202 // If is not an associated field returned value is -1 and no action is made
203 res = bufrdeco_tableB_compressed ( rf, b, & ( seq->lseq[i] ), 1 );
204 if ( res > 0 )
205 {
206 return 1; // case of error
207 }
208 else if ( res == 0 )
209 {
210 // associated field read with success, set again the used elements of r
211 if ( r->nd < ( BUFR_NMAXSEQ - 1 ) )
212 {
213 r->nd += 1;
214 }
215 else
216 {
217 // No more space
218 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): Reached limit. Consider increas BUFR_NMAXSEQ\n", __func__ );
219 return 1;
220 }
221
222 // Update the pointer to the target struct bufrdeco_compressed ref
223 i++; // Update main loop index, note that i is also incrmented at the end of loop.
224 }
225
226
227 break;
228
229 case 1:
230 // Case of replicator descriptor
231 memset ( &replicator, 0, sizeof ( struct bufr_replicator ) ); // mr proper
232 replicator.s = seq;
233 replicator.ixrep = i; // the index of recplicator descriptor in the sequence
234 if ( seq->lseq[i].y != 0 )
235 {
236 // no delayed
237 replicator.ixdel = i; // The index of descriptor with info about actual replication factor
238 replicator.ndesc = seq->lseq[i].x;
239 replicator.nloops = seq->lseq[i].y;
240
241 // Check if this replicator is for a bit-map defining
242 if ( b->state.bitmaping )
243 {
244 b->state.bitmaping = replicator.nloops; // set it properly
245 }
246
247 // call to decode a replicated subsequence
248 bufrdeco_decode_replicated_subsequence_compressed ( r, &replicator, b );
249
250 // and then set again bitamping to 0, because it is finished
251 b->state.bitmaping = 0;
252 }
253 else
254 {
255 // case of delayed;
256 replicator.ixdel = i + 1; // the index of descriptor in sequence with information about the actual amonut of replications
257 replicator.ndesc = seq->lseq[i].x;
258 rf = & ( r->refs[r->nd] );
259
260 // The the data itself to get the loops
261 if ( bufrdeco_tableB_compressed ( rf, b, & ( seq->lseq[ replicator.ixdel ] ), 0 ) )
262 {
263 return 1;
264 }
265
266 // Set the used elements of bufrdeco_compressed_ref
267 if ( r->nd < ( BUFR_NMAXSEQ -1 ) )
268 {
269 r->nd += 1;
270 }
271 else
272 {
273 // No more space
274 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): Reached limit. Consider increas BUFR_NMAXSEQ\n", __func__ );
275 return 1;
276 }
277
278 // Note that is supossed all subsets has the same nlopps,
279 // so the inc_bits must be 0 and nlopps = ref0
280 replicator.nloops = ( size_t ) rf->ref0;
281
282 // Check if this replicator is for a bit-map defining
283 if ( b->state.bitmaping )
284 {
285 b->state.bitmaping = replicator.nloops; // set it properly
286 }
287
288 // call to decode a replicated subsequence
289 bufrdeco_decode_replicated_subsequence_compressed ( r, &replicator, b );
290
291 // and then set again bitamping to 0, because it is finished
292 b->state.bitmaping = 0;
293 }
294 i = replicator.ixdel + replicator.ndesc; // update i properly
295 break;
296
297 case 2:
298 // Case of operator descriptor
299 if ( bufrdeco_parse_f2_compressed ( r, & ( seq->lseq[i] ), b ) )
300 {
301 return 1;
302 }
303 break;
304
305 case 3:
306 // Case of sequence descriptor
307 if ( bufrdeco_parse_compressed_recursive ( r, seq->sons[i], b ) )
308 {
309 return 1;
310 }
311 break;
312
313 default:
314 // this case is not possible
315 snprintf ( b->error, sizeof ( b->error ), "%s(): Found bad 'f' in descriptor '%s' \n", __func__, seq->lseq[i].c );
316 return 1;
317 break;
318 }
319 }
320 return 0;
321}

◆ bufrdeco_parse_tree()

int bufrdeco_parse_tree ( struct bufrdeco *  b)

Parse the tree of descriptors without expand the replicators.

Parameters
bPointer to the source struct bufrdeco

This is the user function to parse the descriptor structure of a BUFR report. This is the first task we need to perform after read the bufr report with the aid of bufrdeco_read_bufr function.

At the end we will get an array of structs bufr_sequence defining the tree

A sequence layer is needed when parsing expanded descriptor sec3 and sec4

First bufr_sequence is the sequence of descriptors in sec3 after byte 8. This is a bufr_sequence in level 0.

When a sequence descriptor is found in a layer, the sequence entries found in table D form this descriptor is a son bufr_sequence. This son has then a father and also can have one or more sons. The index level is incremented by one every step it go into decendents.

And so we go in a recursive way up to the end.

If success return 0, if something went wrong return 1

126}

369 memcpy ( b->sec3.raw, c, b->sec3.length );
370 c += b->sec3.length;
371
372 /******************* section 4 *****************************/
373 b->sec4.length = three_bytes_to_uint32 ( c );
374 // we copy 4 byte more without danger because of latest '7777' and to use fastest exctracting bits algorithm
375 memcpy ( b->sec4.raw, c, b->sec4.length + 4 );
376
377 b->sec4.bit_offset = 32; // the first bit in byte 4
378
379#ifdef DEBUG_TIME
380 bufrdeco_clock_start = clock();
381#endif
382
383 if ( bufr_read_tables ( b ) )
384 {
385 return 1;
386 }
387#ifdef DEBUG_TIME
388 bufrdeco_clock_end = clock();
389 print_timing ( bufrdeco_clock_start, bufrdeco_clock_end,bufr_read_tables_wmo() );
390#endif
391
392 return 0;
393}

◆ bufrdeco_read_bufr()

int bufrdeco_read_bufr ( struct bufrdeco *  b,
char *  filename 
)

Read bufr file and does preliminary and first decode pass.

Parameters
bpointer to struct bufrdeco
filenamecomplete path of BUFR file

This function does the folowing tasks:

  • Read the file and checks the marks at the begining and end to see wheter is a BUFR file
  • Init the structs and allocate the needed memory if not done previously
  • Splits and parse the BUFR sections (without expanding descriptors nor parsing data)
  • Reads the needed Table files and store them in memory.

Returns 0 if all is OK, 1 otherwise

< pointer to a memory buffer where we write raw bufr file

struct bufrdeco *  b 
)

substitute an struct bufr_tables into a struct bufrdeco

Parameters
replacedPointer where to set the replaced pointer
sourcePointer to a struct bufr_tables
bpointer to the container basic struct bufrdeco

Remember that the struct bufr_tables used in bufrdeco library is the one which pointer is in struct bufrdeco . To avoid problems the struct must be initialized before substituted in this fucntion. Both source and replaced structs are not modified.

This is useful if we do not want to read and parse tables again if the caller has a pool of already readed tables.

Returns 0 if succeeded, 1 otherwise

428 snprintf (b->error, sizeof (b->error), "%s(): Cannot get 6 bits for inc_bits from '%s'\n", __func__, d->c );
429 return 1;
430 }
431 r->inc_bits = ival;
432
433 // if is a delayed descriptor then inc_bits MUST be 0.
434 if ( (is_a_delayed_descriptor ( d ) || is_a_short_delayed_descriptor( d ) ) && r->inc_bits )
435 {
436 snprintf (b->error, sizeof (b->error), "%s(): Found a delayed descriptor with inc_bits != 0\n", __func__ );
437 return 1;
438 }
439
440 // Set the bit_offset after all bits needed by this element in all subsets
441 b->state.bit_offset += r->inc_bits * b->sec3.subsets;
442
443 return 0;
444}

Get an int32_t from bits according with bufr criteria to change the reference of a descritor. Most significant bit in source is sign.

Parameters
targetint32_t as result
bitsnumber of bits to consider
sourceuint32_T with the data to transform

Definition at line 224 of file bufrdeco_utils.c.

225{
226 uint32_t mask = 1;
227
228 //bufrdeco_assert (target != NULL);
229
230
231 if ( bits > 32 || bits == 0 )
232 return 1;
233
234 if ( bits > 1 )
235 mask = ( ( uint32_t ) 1 << ( bits - 1 ) );
236
237 if ( mask & source )
238 {
239 // case of negative number
240 *target = - ( int32_t ) ( source - mask );

242 else
243 *target = ( int32_t ) ( source );

◆ get_wmo_tablenames()

int get_wmo_tablenames ( struct bufrdeco *  b)

Get the complete pathnames for WMO csv table files needed by a bufr message.

Parameters
bpointer for a struct bufrdeco

For WMO files this format is adopted BUFR_XX_Y_Z_TableB_en for table B BUFR_XX_Y_Z_CodeFlag for Code table and Flag table. This is equivalent to table C in ECMWF package BUFR_XX_Y_Z_TableD_en for table D

XX is the Version number of master table used Y is the revision (currently ignored) Z is minor revision (currently ignored)

◆ parse_csv_line()

int parse_csv_line ( int *  nt,
char *  tk[],
char *  lin 
)

Parse a csv line.

Parameters
ntpointer to a integer. On success is the number of items found
tkarray of pointers. Every pointer is a item on success
lininput line which is modified in this routine to be splitted into items

This is an optimization of routine parse_csv_line2(). Here we suppose: -All no void items are closed between "" and separed by comas ',' -No " in items. -No blank spaces at the end nor begin of items

NOTE that input line is modified On success return 0, otherwise -1
